{"/service/ndnp/hihouml/batch_hihouml_gonzalo_ver01/data/sn85047084/00294557581/1908012001/0206.xml":{"full_text":"THE PACIFIC COMMERCIAL ADVERTISER, HONOLULU, MONDAY, JANUARY 20, 1908\n1\nPacific Commercial Advertiser\nA MORNING PAPER.\nWALTER G. SMITH\nMONDAY\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK.\nIn his circular of January 4 Henry Clews, the -Sew York financier, says\nthe year opens with \"leading business men in a sober frame of mind and\ngenerally anticipating some trade reaction.\" This he sap is due to recognition\nof the fact that the liquidation and readjustment which has taken place in the\ntoek market must to some degree be expected in mercantile and industrial\ncircles Wiile nobodv expects such a severe reaction therein as has taken place\nin Wall Street Mr Clews observes, \"it is now admitted that the mercantile\ncredit situation is badly strained and that a lower level for commodities must\ntc attained before general business can show any substantial tendency toward\nrecovery.\" Mercantile and industrial readjustment has already begun and,\nince Wall Street was obliged to endure nine months of acute reaction, \"it is\npossible that the period of readjustment in mercantile affairs may occupy a\nfew months to fully straighten things on a permanent basis.\" Further along\nin the circular Mr. Clews sees trade advantages in the situation, where he says:\n\"Our foreign trade is showing not merely a gratifying change, but an en\ncouraging tendency. The decline in merchandise values here encourages exports\nand discourages imports, with the result of leaving a larger balance in our\nfavor.\"\nHr. Clews gives reasons why it does not necessarily follow that the stock\nmarket' should decline in sympathy with depression elsewhere, the gist of them\nteing in this sentence: \"The financial panic began and ended before general\nbusiness felt its 'effect;, the security markets, therefore, are fairly entitled to\nrecovery while the storm is spending its remaining force elsewhere.\" During\nthe past month prices of stocks have been gradually recovering not througb\nupecnlative buying but from the natural tendency to attain a level consonant\n-with the changed conditions. The most important fact in stimulating recov\nery is the improved condition of the money market, which has become evident\noc both sides of the Atlantic. \"It is worth noting, also,\" Mr. Clews says\n\"that a better feeling is developing on the other side regarding American\nsecurities, owing to the fact that we are righting the abuses of mismanagement\nwhich did more to discredit us abroad than the vicissitudes which came from\nlegitimate economic movements.\"\nRegarding the Presidential campaign \"generally an element of more or\nless disturbance\" Mx. Clews holds that, on this occasion, there are no im\nportant unsettling issues at present in sight. Besides the general proposition\nihat Congress never enacts any important legislation in a Presidential year,\nthe great strength of the \"stand patters\" in the present Congress is assurance\nagainst any action on the tariff. Mr. Clews speaks hopefully, however, of the\nprospect that his plan for giving elasticity to the currency may become a\nlaw. The plan is for Congress to authorize national banks to increase their\nordinary circulation by an emergency circulation to the extent of say 20 per\ncent of their paid-up capital, the amount to be limited to $100,000,000, and to\nl e issued upon approved savings bank securities, they to be deposited with the\nComptroller of the Currency. This special issueof currency would be taxed\nto such an extent as to compel the speedy return and cancellation of such notes\nwhen the business needs no longer exist for the additional currency. The plan\nof issuing emergency national bank reserve money would remove the necessity\ntrf a central national bank. Although the latter was being much agitated when\nha wrote, Mr. Clews argues that it would never be acceptable to the national\nbanks. For himself he says of a central bank: \"It would be practically a\nrevival of the old United States Bank, which was a source of so much political\ncorruption, scandal and disaster in President Jackson's time. Therefore, we\nwant no central bank. We have already all the banks we need.. What We do\nneed is to remedy the defects in our currency system, and for this let us labor\nand pray as \"one of the things necessary to our financial salvation.\"\n\nEXPORTS TO \"JAPANESE CHINA.\"\nA new and interesting development in the export trade of the United\nStates is a rapidly growing movement of merchandise to Japanese territory in\nChina. The territory in question, which was in 1898 leased by the Chinese\ngovernment to Russia and transferred from Russian control to that of the\nJapanese government by the treaty which terminated the war between Japan\nand Russia, includes Port Arthur and the adjacent port of Talienwan,' now\nknown as Dalny, with certain adjacent territory, and is the terminus of that\nbranch of the railway which connects the Russia Trans-Siberian line through\nManchuria with Port Arthur and Dalny. To this geographical area, designated\nby the Bureau of Statistics of the Department of .Commerce and Labor as\n'Japanese China,\" the exports from the United States have rapidly increased\nduring the current year until they now exceed one and one-half million dollars\na-month, and seem likely to show for the year just ended a total of ap\nproximately nine million dollars, against less than one-quarter of- a million\ndollars the year before, while during the period in which it was under Russian\ncontrol our direct exports to that territory never reached as much as one\nmillion dollars in any calendar year. The total value of shipments to 'Japa\nnese China\" in the six months ending with December, 1906, was $128,000.\nIn January, 1907, United States exports to \"Japanese China\" were valued\nat $4000, from, which they increased month by month with the exception of\nMay having none credited and August falling off in ratio of increase at the\nrapid rate here shown: February, 127,038; March, 244,871; April, 433,059;\nJune 606,286; July, 697,8S2; August, 433,235; September, 1,539,944; October,\n1,604,553. These figures give a total export trade to the territory in question,\nfor the first ten months of 1907, of $5,690,868. Should the November and\nDecember totals run at the rate of those of September and October, the total\nfor the year would be nearly nine million dollars.\nThis new movement of merchandise from the United States to Japanese\nterritory in China is especially interesting both in view of the interest felt\nregarding the effect of Japanese occupation upon American trade with that\nsection of China and the relation of this movement to the figures of our trade\nwith China proper. Our total exports to the Chinese Empire for the ten months\nending with October, 1907, are $20,432,000, against $26,400,000 in the same\nmonths of the preceding year; and if this movement to Japanese China be\nconsidered in conjunction with the exports to the Chinese Empire the aggregate\nto the Chinese Empire and Japanese China would be slightly in excess of that\n-of the corresponding months of 1906. How much of this merchandise passing\nto \"Japanese China\" passes thence to China proper can not, of course, be\ndetermined, though the fact that the class of merchandise forming the bulk of\nthis total consists of street cars, rails, for railways, structural iron and steel,\nand other articles of this class suggests that it is largely for use in the cities\nand railway lines within the territory designated as \"Japanese China.\"\nTHE TERRITORIAL COLLEGE,\nAttention is especially invited to the information given in this issue\nregarding the preliminary activities of the College of Agriculture and Mechanic\nArts. The short course to be offered in horticulture and entomology is an\nopportunity of which a large number should be ready to take advantage, as\nthe instruction to be imparted therein bears directly upon various local in\ndustries as well as attractive home keeping.\nOf greater importance, however, to the future of the college directly, and of\nthe Territory through the work of the institution, is the short preparatory\neonrse, to begin on the third of February, designed to fit intending regular\nstudents for the four years' course leading to the degree of Bachelor of\nScience. From present appearances the greatest initial task in placing the\ncollege on a creditable working basis will be that of obtaining a sufficient\nnumber of students to look like a school. Practically all the presently eligible\nyouth are now taking the regular courses of the public and private colleges,\nseminaries and high schools. They would have to break with these institutions\nto enter the College of Agriculture and Mechanic Arts; which is a step of\nenough seriousness to require great and well-advised consideration before taking.\nActing Dean Pope has already conferred with other educationists on this mat\nter, and perhaps the problem can best be solved by a set conference of the\ncollege authorities and principals of the various higher schools, public and\nprivate, 'of the Territory. It may be necessary, or at least advisable, to adopt\nprocess of selection by those best acquainted with eligibles now in school,\nalong with the proffer of free choice of the college course on the part of the\nyouth and their parents or guardians. At all events, a great effort should be\nmade by those taking an interest in the new institution to have it start with\na creditable attendance.\n\nA flaw was discovered in a new Gaming Act of Xew Zealand, from being\nbehind the times in neglecting to prohibit the announcement of dividends by\nphonograph.\nEDITOR\nJANUARY 20\nSOLD OPIUM WITHOUT\nHAVING A LICENSE\nThe first case in which the local po\nlice have been able to catch an illicit\nseller of opium redhanded for a.long\ntime, occurred last night. An old\nChinaman named Pak Chew, who con\nducts an opium den on King: 'street in\nthe big building: opposite Kalakaua\navenue, was arrested on the charge\nmentioned. It happened that the po\nlice arrived just at the right moment.\nPak Chew had his scales out and was\nweighing the drug for one of his cus\ntomers, who had the money already on\nthe table before him. Under the local\nlaws it is hard to obtain evidence of\nthe kind needed to obtain a conviction\nin an offense of this kind, but Chief\nTaylor believes that he has a. case\nwhich Is sure to bring about a convic\ntion when presented in court.\nCHOICE WHICH\nJOSES IDE\n(Continued from Pasre One.)\nthere was nothing better. Tti.re ian\nbe no explanation of it except that\nwhich the Bible gives. It was by faith\nthat he chose. Where did he get that\nfaith? \"Where we all get it from his\nmother. From her he had learned to\nregard eachof those Hebrew slaves,\ntoiling In embittered brutishness, as a\nbrother, and for every agony that rent\ntheir hearts a kindred ageny smote his\nown.\n\"No doubt it cost hh- a struggle.\nHis \"very education and ex. -tenee and\ngenerosity of soul fitted hin appre\nciate what he was giving up. For the\nEgyptian kingdom which he was giv\ning up, he saw an everlasting king\ndom. And was not his choice abund\nantly justified? Coming back from his\nexile with his brother Aaron he stood\nbefore that puissant PhaTaoh and de\nmanded that he let his people go. He\norganized that people whose long slav\nery had driven out the very idea of\nliberty and fitted them to be the chan\nnels through which the oracles of God\nwere communicated to mankind. His\ntory begins with Moses, and his legis\nlation has been engrafted into that of\nevery civilized nation.\n\"Was not such a man entitled to a\ngreat funeral? But he had a sublimer\nsepulture than any man could have\ngiven him.\n\"'By Nebo's lonely mountain\nOn this side Jordan's wave;\nIn a vale in the land of Moab\nThere lies a lonely grave.\n'But no man digged that sepul\nchre\nArid no man saw it e'er\nFor the angel of God upturned fhe\nsod\nAnd laid the good man there.'\n\"When greetings were to be brought\nt Christ from the past ages it-was\nMoses and Elias who were delegated\nto bring them on the mount of trans\nfiguration. In the apocalypse the song\nthat was sung was the song of Moses\nand the Lamb.\"\n\nSUNRISE PRAYER MEETING.\nAs part of the devotions connected\nwith the Methodist Conference, a sun-\nrise prayer meeting was held J on\nPunchbowl summit on Sunday. Gener\nal Secretary Paul Super of the Y. M.\nC. A. accompanied the praise with the\ncornet and Mrs. Pitkin was the organ\nist. Dr. and Mrs. Crane were the lead\ners. Tiere were thirty-five worshipers\npresent.\n\nSQUADRON FOR CHINA.\nThe San Francisco Examiner says a\nrumor is in circulation at Mare Island\nthat Admiral Swinburne is to be rush\ned to China with a squadron when the\nbig fleet under Admiral Evans reaches\nthe Coast. It is stated to be certain\nthat the flagship Charleston and he\ncruisers Milwaukee and St. Louis will\nbe included 'in the squadron. Rumors\nof threatened Boxer uprisings are giv\nen as the cause.\nHOME OF THE HUMMING BIRD.\nThe home of the humming bird is\none of the most remarkable and artistic\ncreations of all bird architecture. It\nis a tiny, delicate cup, made of the soft\nest plant down, saddled upon some\nrather slender branch. The saliva of\nthe birds is used to compact and secure\nthe material, and likewise to coat the\nexterior with the gray-green lichens so\ngenerally found upon trees. This makes\nit so assimilate with the surroundings\nthat it is a very difficult object to dis\ncover. And thereby hangs a tale. A\ngentleman had told me that, if I would\ncall upon him, he would show me an\noccupied nest of a humming bird in\nhis orchard. When I came, he was out\nof town, but I thought I would see if\nI could not find the nest myself. So\nI made inspection from tree to tree,\nand presently the female hummer be\ngan to fly about me anxiously. We\nplayed a game of hot and cold, until it\nbecame evident that the nest must be\nin a certain low apple tree which had\nmany dead lichen-covered branches.\nSome of these came down nearly to the\nground, and for quite a while I stood\nby the tree running my eyes along each\nbranch in order, trying to make out the\nnest, while the female kept darting\nfrantically at my head. It must have\nbeen nearly a quarter of an hour before\nI discovered that I was standing al\nmost touching the nest with my hands,\nhaving been looking right over it all\nthe time. It contained two fresh eggs,\nthis being in the early part of June.\nThe branch upon which it was built\nwas completely overgrown with lichens,\nand the nest being covered with them,\ntoo, was wonderfully disguised, though\nthere were no leaves to hide it.\nOuting.\nMY LADY\nmay do without a new picture\nhat, or wear a last -year's pair of\nshoes; but she must have a\nor know the reason why. One\nreason why she should have it\nis the fine line of manicure ac\ncessories we have on display.\nSteel scissors and nail -files of\nevery description; cuticle knives,\ncorn knives, etc.\nThe very best grade at reason\nable prices.\nHOLLISTER DRUG GO.\nFORT STREET\n\"At New York Prices'\nThat's the Way We Sell\nWe have made a specialty of sell\ning silverware cheaply and we guar\nantee to you that our Silver Knives,\nForks, Spoons and Fancy Pieces\ncan not be purchased for less money\nanywhere.\nWe ask you to Inspect our stock!\n\nH. F. Wichman Co.\nLIMITED\nLeading Jewelers\nBest Water\nIn the city.\nm I If F m\nsfiiieo water\nfrom our own. Artesian Well on the\npremises used for all drinking and\ncooking purposes at\nAlexander Young Cafe\nALEXANDER YOUNG BLDG.\nREAD THE ADVERTISER\nWORLD'S NEWS DAILY\nOf\nand\nis now in full swing, and while\nmany of the numbers were closed\nout during the first rush, still the\nofferings were so many and varied\nthat many choice bargains are yet\nto be had.\n\"Ehlers' Bargains Satisfy.\"\nn\nIG Ob\nem\nm\nOUR\nt\nERS\nmn ay?\ndo people still carry around\nsooty chimneys, wick-cleaning1,\nCome out of the rut be\nand saves lots of worry and\nYou will never have to\nyour house wired by the\nHawaiian Electric Company, Ltd.\nKing Street near Alakea.\nThe\nAfter washing, shake off the superfluouswater and give\na bath of Colonial Spirits, which will so accelerate the drying\nthat the plates will be ready in a very short time.\nMany think that plates so treated print better than when\ndried the old-fashioned way.\nLewers\n177 S. King \"Street.\nAGENTS.\nii\ntrawberry\nThe cream that adds much to this lovely fruit is\nto be had from us fresh every day. You cannot\nget a more satisfactory article.\nMetropolitan Meat Company, Ltd,\nTelephone 45.\nwr .M.\nThe Best J\nSays \"PRIMO EVERY TIME He\nhas tried them all, and knows.\nHe is a poor judge of Primo, and a\npoor judge of beers who has tried\nmost of the others, but not Primo.\nRight?\nYou can make $250 per acre\nin Kalihi Valley is an ideal place for growing of Pineapples.\nThe right soil, the right climate. Pineapples grow there now.\nLet me take you out to show them to you. Three miles from the\nbusiness center of Honolulu, 1 1-2 miles from the Pineapple Cannery.\nWill sell the land at from\n$250 to $400 Per Acre\nON EASY TERMS.\nCAMPBELL BLOCK, FORT STREET.\nthe old-fashioned lamp, with its\nand match-striking?\nup-to-date! It's just as cheap,\nbother.\nread with poor light if you have\nPhone 390\nPleasures of\nAmateur\nPhotography\nare greatly increased if the drying\nof the plates is hastened with\noloiiislo lots\nCooke, Ltd.\nPhone Exchange 20\nDays\nudge\nfrom one season's crop\nMM\nNtAPPLES S\nLA II El\n1\nV","height":"33476","width":"22444"}}
